# gRPC Patterns

## Invariant

All gRPC service methods **must** throw `RpcException` (from `@nestjs/microservices`).
HTTP exception classes (`HttpException`, `BadRequestException`, `NotFoundException`, etc.)
are **forbidden** inside gRPC code paths.

## Correct

```typescript
import { RpcException } from '@nestjs/microservices';
import { status } from '@grpc/grpc-js';

async getUser(request: GetUserRequest): Promise<GetUserResponse> {
  const user = await this.userRepository.find(request.id);
  if (!user) {
    throw new RpcException({
      code: status.NOT_FOUND,
      message: `User ${request.id} not found`,
    });
  }
  return { user };
}
```

## Forbidden

```typescript
// ❌ HTTP exception in a gRPC handler — caller gets UNKNOWN (2) on the wire
throw new NotFoundException(`User ${id} not found`);

// ❌ Raw HTTP status code — means nothing to a gRPC client
throw new HttpException('Bad input', 400);

// ❌ Bare Error — loses gRPC status enum entirely
throw new Error('User not found');
```

## Rationale

gRPC clients read `status.code`, not HTTP status codes. Throwing an HTTP exception in
a gRPC handler produces an `UNKNOWN (2)` status to the caller, discarding all structured
error data. `RpcException` wrapping a `@grpc/grpc-js` status enum maps correctly to what
the generated client expects.

## Proto contracts

When adding a new RPC method to a `.proto` file, implement the corresponding service
handler in the same PR. Committed stubs without handlers break generated clients.
